# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: federated-learning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] In the context of medical data, anonymized data refers to data from which the patient cannot be identified by the recipient of the information.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] The name, address, and full postcode must be removed, together with any other information which, in conjunction with other data held by or disclosed to the recipient, could identify the patient.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] There will always be a risk that anonymized data may not stay anonymous over time.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] Pairing the anonymized dataset with other data, clever techniques and raw power are some of the ways previously anonymous data sets have become de-anonymized; The data subjects are no longer anonymous.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] De-anonymization is the reverse process in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other data sources to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] Generalization and perturbation are the two popular anonymization approaches for relational data.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] The process of obscuring data with the ability to re-identify it later is also called pseudonymization and is one way companies can store data in a way that is HIPAA compliant.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] However, according to ARTICLE 29 DATA PROTECTION WORKING PARTY, Directive 95/46/EC refers to anonymisation in Recital 26 "signifies that to anonymise any data, the data must be stripped of sufficient elements such that the data subject can no longer be identified.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] More precisely, that data must be processed in such a way that it can no longer be used to identify a natural person by using “all the means likely reasonably to be used” by either the controller or a third party.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] An important factor is that the processing must be irreversible.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] The Directive does not clarify how such a de-identification process should or could be performed.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] The focus is on the outcome: that data should be such as not to allow the data subject to be identified via “all” “likely” and “reasonable” means.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] Reference is made to codes of conduct as a tool to set out possible anonymisation mechanisms as well as retention in a form in which identification of the data subject is “no longer possible”.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] There are five types of data anonymization operations: generalization, suppression, anatomization, permutation, and perturbation.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) requires that stored data on people in the EU undergo either anonymization or a pseudonymization process.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] According to the EDPS and AEPD, no one, including the data controller, should be able to re-identify data subjects in a properly anonymized dataset.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] Research by data scientists at Imperial College in London and UCLouvain in Belgium, as well as a ruling by Judge Michal Agmon-Gonen of the Tel Aviv District Court, highlight the shortcomings of "Anonymisation" in today's big data world.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] Anonymisation reflects an outdated approach to data protection that was developed when the processing of data was limited to isolated (siloed) applications, prior to the popularity of big data processing involving the widespread sharing and combining of data.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] Removing identifying metadata from computer files is important for anonymizing them.
[src:federated-learning/data-anonymization] Metadata removal tools are useful for achieving this.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Another way to describe differential privacy is as a constraint on the algorithms used to publish aggregate information about a statistical database which limits the disclosure of private information of records in the database.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Roughly, an algorithm is differentially private if an observer seeing its output cannot tell whether a particular individual's information was used in the computation.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Differential privacy is often discussed in the context of identifying individuals whose information may be in a database.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Although it does not directly refer to identification and reidentification attacks, differentially private algorithms provably resist such attacks.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The 2006 Cynthia Dwork, Frank McSherry, Kobbi Nissim, and Adam D.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Smith article introduced the concept of ε-differential privacy, a mathematical definition for the privacy loss associated with any data release drawn from a statistical database.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The definition of ε-differential privacy requires that a change to one entry in a database only creates a small change in the probability distribution of the outputs of measurements, as seen by the attacker.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The intuition for the definition of ε-differential privacy is that a person's privacy cannot be compromised by a statistical release if their data are not in the database.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In differential privacy, each individual is given roughly the same privacy that would result from having their data removed.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] That is, the statistical functions run on the database should not be substantially affected by the removal, addition, or change of any individual in the data.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] How much any individual contributes to the result of a database query depends in part on how many people's data are involved in the query.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If the database contains data from a single person, that person's data contributes 100%.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If the database contains data from a hundred people, each person's data contributes just 1%.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The key insight of differential privacy is that as the query is made on the data of fewer and fewer people, more noise needs to be added to the query result to produce the same amount of privacy.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Let ε be a positive real number and ${\mathcal {A}}$ be a randomized algorithm that takes a dataset as input (representing the actions of the trusted party holding the data).
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Let ${\textrm {im}}\ {\mathcal {A}}$ denote the image of ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] where the probability is taken over the randomness used by the algorithm.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This definition is sometimes called "approximate differential privacy", with "pure differential privacy" being a special case when $\delta =0$ .
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In the latter case, the algorithm is commonly said to satisfy ε-differential privacy (i.e., omitting $\delta =0$ ).
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Differential privacy offers strong and robust guarantees that facilitate modular design and analysis of differentially private mechanisms due to its composability, robustness to post-processing, and graceful degradation in the presence of correlated data.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] According to this definition, differential privacy is a condition on the release mechanism (i.e., the trusted party releasing information *about* the dataset) and not on the dataset itself.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Intuitively, this means that for any two datasets that are similar, a given differentially private algorithm will behave approximately the same on both datasets.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The definition gives a strong guarantee that presence or absence of an individual will not affect the final output of the algorithm significantly.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] For example, assume we have a database of medical records $D_{1}$ where each record is a pair (**Name**, **X**), where X is a Boolean denoting whether a person has diabetes or not.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Now suppose a malicious user (often termed an *adversary*) wants to find whether Chandler has diabetes or not.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Suppose he also knows in which row of the database Chandler resides.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Now suppose the adversary is only allowed to use a particular form of query $Q_{i}$ that returns the partial sum of the first i rows of column X in the database.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In order to find Chandler's diabetes status the adversary executes $Q_{5}(D_{1})$ and $Q_{4}(D_{1})$ , then computes their difference.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This indicates that the "Has Diabetes" field in Chandler's row must be 1.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This example highlights how individual information can be compromised even without explicitly querying for the information of a specific individual.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Continuing this example, if we construct $D_{2}$ by replacing (Chandler, 1) with (Chandler, 0) then this malicious adversary will be able to distinguish $D_{2}$ from $D_{1}$ by computing $Q_{5}-Q_{4}$ for each dataset.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If the adversary were required to receive the values $Q_{i}$ via an $\varepsilon$ -differentially private algorithm, for a sufficiently small $\varepsilon$ , then he or she would be unable to distinguish between the two datasets.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Composability refers to the fact that the joint distribution of the outputs of (possibly adaptively chosen) differentially private mechanisms satisfies differential privacy.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The other important property for modular use of differential privacy is robustness to post processing.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This is defined to mean that for any deterministic or randomized function F defined over the image of the mechanism ${\mathcal {A}}$ , if ${\mathcal {A}}$ satisfies ε-differential privacy, so does $F({\mathcal {A}})$ .
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The property of composition permits modular construction and analysis of differentially private mechanisms and motivates the concept of the *privacy loss budget*.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If all elements that access sensitive data of a complex mechanisms are separately differentially private, so will be their combination, followed by arbitrary post-processing.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In general, ε-differential privacy is designed to protect the privacy between neighboring databases which differ only in one row.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This means that no adversary with arbitrary auxiliary information can know if **one** particular participant submitted their information.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] We may want to protect databases differing in c rows, which amounts to an adversary with arbitrary auxiliary information knowing if **c** particular participants submitted their information.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In other words, instead of having each item ε-differentially private protected, now every group of c items is ε-differentially private protected (and each item is $(\varepsilon /c)$ -differentially private protected).
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] One can think of differential privacy as bounding the error rates in a hypothesis test.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Since differential privacy is a probabilistic concept, any differentially private mechanism is necessarily randomized.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Some of these, like the Laplace mechanism, described below, rely on adding controlled noise to the function that we want to compute.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Others, like the exponential mechanism and posterior sampling sample from a problem-dependent family of distributions instead.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] An important definition with respect to ε-differentially private mechanisms is sensitivity.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Let d be a positive integer, ${\mathcal {D}}$ be a collection of datasets, and $f\colon {\mathcal {D}}\rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ be a function.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In the example of the medical database below, if we consider f to be the function $Q_{i}$ , then the sensitivity of the function is one, since changing any one of the entries in the database causes the output of the function to change by either zero or one.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This can be generalized to other metric spaces (measures of distance), and must be to make certain differentially private algorithms work, including adding noise from the Gaussian distribution (which requires the L2 norm) instead of the Laplace distribution.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] There are techniques (which are described below) using which we can create a differentially private algorithm for functions, with parameters that vary depending on their sensitivity.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The Laplace mechanism adds Laplace noise (i.e. noise from the Laplace distribution, which can be expressed by probability density function ${\text{noise}}(y)\propto \exp(-|y|/\lambda )\,\!$ , which has mean zero and standard deviation ${\sqrt {2}}\lambda \,\!$ ).
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] We can consider ${\frac {\Delta (f)}{\lambda }}\,\!$ to be the privacy factor $\varepsilon \,\!$ .
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Thus ${\mathcal {T}}\,\!$ follows a differentially private mechanism (as can be seen from the definition above).
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If we try to use this concept in our diabetes example then it follows from the above derived fact that in order to have ${\mathcal {A}}\,\!$ as the $\varepsilon \,\!$ -differential private algorithm we need to have $\lambda =1/\varepsilon \,\!$ .
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Though we have used Laplace noise here, other forms of noise, such as the Gaussian Noise, can be employed, but they may require a slight relaxation of the definition of differential privacy.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If heads, then toss the coin again (ignoring the outcome), and answer the question honestly.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If tails, then toss the coin again and answer "Yes" if heads, "No" if tails.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] (The seemingly redundant extra toss in the first case is needed in situations where just the *act* of tossing a coin may be observed by others, even if the actual result stays hidden.) The confidentiality then arises from the refutability of the individual responses.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] But, overall, these data with many responses are significant, since positive responses are given to a quarter by people who do not have the *attribute A* and three-quarters by people who actually possess it.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Thus, if *p* is the true proportion of people with *A*, then we expect to obtain (1/4)(1-*p*) + (3/4)*p* = (1/4) + *p*/2 positive responses.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In particular, if the *attribute A* is synonymous with illegal behavior, then answering "Yes" is not incriminating, insofar as the person has a probability of a "Yes" response, whatever it may be.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] A transformation T is c -stable if the Hamming distance between $T(A)$ and $T(B)$ is at most c -times the Hamming distance between A and B for any two databases $A,B$ .
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] If there is a mechanism M that is $\varepsilon$ -differentially private, then the composite mechanism $M\circ T$ is $(\varepsilon \times c)$ -differentially private.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This could be generalized to group privacy, as the group size could be thought of as the Hamming distance h between A and B (where A contains the group and B does not).
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In this case $M\circ T$ is $(\varepsilon \times c\times h)$ -differentially private.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In 1977, Tore Dalenius formalized the mathematics of cell suppression.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Tore Dalenius was a Swedish statistician who contributed to statistical privacy through his 1977 paper that revealed a key point about statistical databases, which was that databases should not reveal information about an individual that is not otherwise accessible.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] He also defined a typology for statistical disclosures.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Schwartz formalized the concept of a Tracker, an adversary that could learn the confidential contents of a statistical database by creating a series of targeted queries and remembering the results.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This and future research showed that privacy properties in a database could only be preserved by considering each new query in light of (possibly all) previous queries.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This line of work is sometimes called *query privacy,* with the final result being that tracking the impact of a query on the privacy of individuals in the database was NP-hard.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] The general phenomenon is known as the Fundamental Law of Information Recovery, and its key insight, namely that in the most general case, privacy cannot be protected without injecting some amount of noise, led to development of differential privacy.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] In 2006, Cynthia Dwork, Frank McSherry, Kobbi Nissim and Adam D.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Smith published an article formalizing the amount of noise that needed to be added and proposing a generalized mechanism for doing so.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] This paper also created the first formal definition of differential privacy.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Their work was a co-recipient of the 2016 TCC Test-of-Time Award and the 2017 Gödel Prize.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Since then, subsequent research has shown that there are many ways to produce very accurate statistics from the database while still ensuring high levels of privacy.
[src:federated-learning/differential-privacy] Because differential privacy techniques are implemented on real computers, they are vulnerable to various attacks not possible to compensate for solely in the mathematics of the techniques themselves.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:federated-learning/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:federated-learning/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning is generally concerned with and motivated by issues such as data privacy, data minimization, and data access rights.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Its applications involve a variety of research areas including defence, telecommunications, the Internet of things, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning aims at training a machine learning algorithm, for instance deep neural networks, on multiple local datasets contained in local nodes without explicitly exchanging data samples.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The general principle consists in training local models on local data samples and exchanging parameters (e.g. the weights and biases of a deep neural network) between these local nodes at some frequency to generate a global model shared by all nodes.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The main difference between federated learning and distributed learning lies in the assumptions made on the properties of the local datasets, as distributed learning originally aims at parallelizing computing power where federated learning originally aims at training on heterogeneous datasets.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] While distributed learning also aims at training a single model on multiple servers, a common underlying assumption is that the local datasets are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) and roughly have the same size.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] None of these hypotheses are made for federated learning; instead, the datasets are typically heterogeneous and their sizes may span several orders of magnitude.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Moreover, the clients involved in federated learning may be unreliable as they are subject to more failures or drop out since they commonly rely on less powerful communication media (i.e.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Wi-Fi) and battery-powered systems (i.e. smartphones and IoT devices) compared to distributed learning where nodes are typically datacenters that have powerful computational capabilities and are connected to one another with fast networks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] where K is the number of nodes, $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ are the weights of model as viewed by node i , and $f_{i}$ is node i 's local objective function, which describes how model weights $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ conforms to node i 's local dataset.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In the centralized federated learning setting, a central server is used to orchestrate the different steps of the algorithms and coordinate all the participating nodes during the learning process.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The server is responsible for the nodes selection at the beginning of the training process and for the aggregation of the received model updates.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Since all the selected nodes have to send updates to a single entity, the server may become a bottleneck of the system.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In the decentralized federated learning setting, the nodes are able to coordinate themselves to obtain the global model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This setup prevents single point failures as the model updates are exchanged only between interconnected nodes without the orchestration of the central server.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Nevertheless, the specific network topology may affect the performances of the learning process.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] See blockchain-based federated learning and the references therein.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In many application domains, not all clients are the same.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Clients may share the same model architecture, but each have a different data distribution—which is known as Personalized federated learning (PFL), or even have different model architectures, like mobile phones and IoT devices—which is known as Heterogeneous federated learning.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The key challenge in training a PFL model is to keep each client different from others, and at the same time benefit from generalizing across clients.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Most of the existing federated learning strategies assume that local models share the same global model architecture.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In 2020, a federated learning framework named HeteroFL was developed to address heterogeneous clients equipped with very different computation and communication capabilities.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The HeteroFL technique can enable the training of heterogeneous local models with dynamically varying computation and non-IID data complexities while still producing a single accurate global inference model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The iterative process of federated learning is composed of a series of fundamental client-server interactions, each of which is known as a federated learning round.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In the methodology below, a central server is used for aggregation, while local nodes perform local training depending on the central server's orders.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] However, other strategies lead to the same results without central servers, in a peer-to-peer approach, using gossip or consensus methodologies.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] **Client selection**: a fraction of local nodes are selected to start training on local data.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The selected nodes acquire the current statistical model while the others wait for the next federated round.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] **Configuration**: the central server orders selected nodes to undergo training of the model on their local data in a pre-specified fashion (e.g., for some mini-batch updates of gradient descent).
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] **Reporting**: each selected node sends its local model to the server for aggregation.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The central server aggregates the received models and sends back the model updates to the nodes.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] It also handles failures for disconnected nodes or lost model updates.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The next federated round is started returning to the client selection phase.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] **Termination**: once a pre-defined termination criterion is met (e.g., a maximum number of iterations is reached or the model accuracy is greater than a threshold) the central server aggregates the updates and finalizes the global model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The procedure considered before assumes synchronized model updates.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Recent federated learning developments introduced novel techniques to tackle asynchronicity during the training process, or training with dynamically varying models.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Compared to synchronous approaches where local models are exchanged once the computations have been performed for all layers of the neural network, asynchronous ones leverage the properties of neural networks to exchange model updates as soon as the computations of a certain layer are available.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] These techniques are also commonly referred to as split learning and they can be applied both at training and inference time regardless of centralized or decentralized federated learning settings.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In most cases, the assumption of independent and identically distributed samples across local nodes does not hold for federated learning setups.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Under this setting, the performances of the training process may vary significantly according to the unbalanced local data samples as well as the particular probability distribution of the training examples (i.e., features and labels) stored at the local nodes.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] To further investigate the effects of non-IID data, the following description considers the main categories presented in the preprint by Peter Kairouz et al. from 2019.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The description of non-IID data relies on the analysis of the joint probability between features and labels for each node.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This allows decoupling of each contribution according to the specific distribution available at the local nodes.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The loss in accuracy due to non-iid data can be bounded through using more sophisticated means of doing data normalization, rather than batch normalization.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The way the statistical local outputs are pooled and the way the nodes communicate with each other can change from the centralized model explained in the previous section.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This leads to a variety of federated learning approaches: for instance no central orchestrating server, or stochastic communication.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In particular, orchestrator-less distributed networks are one important variation.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In this case, there is no central server dispatching queries to local nodes and aggregating local models.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Each local node sends its outputs to several randomly-selected others, which aggregate their results locally.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This restrains the number of transactions, thereby sometimes reducing training time and computing cost.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Those parameters have to be optimized depending on the constraints of the machine learning application (e.g., available computing power, available memory, bandwidth).
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] For instance, stochastically choosing a limited fraction C of nodes for each iteration diminishes computing cost and may prevent overfitting, in the same way that stochastic gradient descent can reduce overfitting.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning requires frequent communication between nodes during the learning process.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Thus, it requires not only enough local computing power and memory, but also high bandwidth connections to be able to exchange parameters of the machine learning model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] However, the technology also avoids data communication, which can require significant resources before starting centralized machine learning.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Governance considerations may also limit the applicability of federated learning, in particular when applied in cross-organisational settings.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Most federated learning frameworks rely on a central coordinating server, which introduces questions regarding infrastructure control, model ownership, and decision-making authority among collaborators.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In multi-party deployments, especially those spanning competitive or collaborative data markets, the absence of agreed-upon governance structures can create uncertainty about responsibilities for validating model updates, auditing system behaviour, and managing security incidents.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] These organisational issues may deter participants from contributing to shared models and can complicate regulatory compliance, thereby constraining adoption.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] A further governance-related issue concerns the distribution of value among participants as multi-party federated learning systems scale.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] As more clients contribute to training, model accuracy may approach a performance threshold, after which additional contributions yield diminishing marginal utility.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This dynamic can create tensions within collaborative arrangements, as early participants may perceive later contributions as offering reduced value while still benefiting from the shared model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Such asymmetries may affect incentives to join or remain in a consortium and complicate the design of fair participation, ownership, or reward structures.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Establishing transparent rules for contribution assessment and benefit allocation is therefore an important organisational challenge and represents a direction for future research.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] A number of different algorithms for federated optimization have been proposed.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Stochastic gradient descent is an approach used in deep learning, where gradients are computed on a random subset of the total dataset and then used to make one step of the gradient descent..
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated stochastic gradient descent is the analog of this algorithm to the federated setting, but uses a random subset of the nodes, each node using all its data.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The server averages the gradients in proportion to the number of training data on each node, and uses the average to make a gradient descent step.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated averaging (FedAvg) is a generalization of FedSGD which allows nodes to do more than one batch update on local data and exchange updated weights rather than gradients.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This reduces communication and is equivalent to averaging the weights if all nodes start with the same weights.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] It does not seem to hurt the resulting averaged model's performance compared to FedSGD.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] FedAvg variations have been proposed based on adaptive optimizers such as ADAM and AdaGrad, and tend to outperform FedAvg.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated Proximal (FedProx) extends FedAvg by adding a proximal term to the local objective in the form of ${\frac {\mu }{2}}\|w-w^{t}\|^{2}$ , where $\mu$ is the FedProx hyper parameter, in order to address data heterogeneity across clients.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The proximal term constrains local updates, helping reduce client drift when client data are non-IID.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning methods suffer when node datasets are distributed heterogeneously, because then minimizing the node losses is not the same as minimizing the global loss.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In 2021, Acar et al. introduced a solution called FedDyn, which dynamically regularizes each node loss function so that they converge to the global loss.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Since the local losses are aligned, FedDyn is robust to the different heterogeneity levels and so it can safely perform full minimization in each device.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In theory, FedDyn converges to the optimal (a stationary point for nonconvex losses) by being agnostic to the heterogeneity levels.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] These claims are verified with extensive experiments on various datasets.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Besides reducing communication, it is also beneficial to reduce local computation.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] To do this, FedDynOneGD modifies FedDyn to calculate only one gradient per node per round, regularizes it and updates the global model with it.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Hence, the computational complexity is linear in local dataset size.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Moreover, gradient computation can be parallelized on each node, unlike successive SGD steps.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In theory, FedDynOneGD achieves the same convergence guarantees as in FedDyn with less local computation.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning methods have poor global performance under non-IID settings.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This motivates clients to yield personalized models in federation.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] To change this, Vahidian et al. recently introduced the algorithm Sub-FedAvg which does hybrid pruning (structured and unstructured pruning) with averaging on the intersection of clients' drawn subnetworks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This simultaneously addresses communication efficiency, resource constraints and personalized models accuracies.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Sub-FedAvg also extends the "lottery ticket hypothesis" of centrally trained neural networks to federated learning, with the research question: "Do winning tickets exist for clients' neural networks being trained in federated learning?
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] If so, how to effectively draw the personalized subnetworks for each client?" Sub-FedAvg experimentally answers "yes" and proposes two algorithms to effectively draw the personalized subnetworks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] IDA (Inverse Distance Aggregation) is a novel adaptive weighting approach for federated learning nodes based on meta-information which handles unbalanced and non-iid data.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] It uses the distance of the model parameters as a strategy to minimize the effect of outliers and improve the model's convergence rate.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Very few methods for hybrid federated learning, where clients only hold subsets of both features and samples, exist.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Yet, this scenario is very important in practical settings.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Hybrid Federated Dual Coordinate Ascent (HyFDCA) is a novel algorithm proposed in 2024 that solves convex problems in the hybrid FL setting.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This algorithm extends CoCoA, a primal-dual distributed optimization algorithm introduced by Jaggi et al.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] (2017), to the case where both samples and features are partitioned across clients.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] There is only one other algorithm that focuses on hybrid FL, HyFEM proposed by Zhang et al.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This algorithm uses a feature matching formulation that balances clients building accurate local models and the server learning an accurate global model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This requires a matching regularizer constant that must be tuned based on user goals and results in disparate local and global models.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Furthermore, the convergence results provided for HyFEM only prove convergence of the matching formulation not of the original global problem.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] This work is substantially different from HyFDCA's approach which uses data on local clients to build a global model that converges to the same solution as if the model was trained centrally.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Furthermore, the local and global models are synchronized and do not require the adjustment of a matching parameter between local and global models.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] However, HyFEM is suitable for a vast array of architectures including deep learning architectures, whereas HyFDCA is designed for convex problems like logistic regression and support vector machines.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] HyFDCA is empirically benchmarked against the aforementioned HyFEM as well as the popular FedAvg in solving convex problem (specifically classification problems) for several popular datasets (MNIST, Covtype, and News20).
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The authors found HyFDCA converges to a lower loss value and higher validation accuracy in less overall time in 33 of 36 comparisons examined and 36 of 36 comparisons examined with respect to the number of outer iterations.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Lastly, HyFDCA only requires tuning of one hyperparameter, the number of inner iterations, as opposed to FedAvg (which requires tuning three) or HyFEM (which requires tuning four).
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In addition to FedAvg and HyFEM being quite difficult to optimize hyperparameters in turn greatly affecting convergence, HyFDCA's single hyperparameter allows for simpler practical implementations and hyperparameter selection methodologies.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning has started to emerge as an important research topic in 2015 and 2016, with the first publications on federated averaging in telecommunication settings.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Before that, in a thesis work titled "A Framework for Multi-source Prefetching Through Adaptive Weight", an approach to aggregate predictions from multiple models trained at three location of a request response cycle with was proposed.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Another important aspect of active research is the reduction of the communication burden during the federated learning process.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In 2017 and 2018, publications have emphasized the development of resource allocation strategies, especially to reduce communication requirements between nodes with gossip algorithms as well as on the characterization of the robustness to differential privacy attacks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Other research activities focus on the reduction of the bandwidth during training through sparsification and quantization methods, where the machine learning models are sparsified and/or compressed before they are shared with other nodes.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Developing ultra-light DNN architectures is essential for device-/edge- learning and recent work recognises both the energy efficiency requirements for future federated learning and the need to compress deep learning, especially during learning.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Recent research advancements are starting to consider real-world propagating channels as in previous implementations ideal channels were assumed.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Another active direction of research is to develop Federated learning for training heterogeneous local models with varying computation complexities and producing a single powerful global inference model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] A learning framework named Assisted learning was recently developed to improve each agent's learning capabilities without transmitting private data, models, and even learning objectives.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Compared with Federated learning that often requires a central controller to orchestrate the learning and optimization, Assisted learning aims to provide protocols for the agents to optimize and learn among themselves without a global model.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning typically applies when individual actors need to train models on larger datasets than their own, but cannot afford to share the data in itself with others (e.g., for legal, strategic or economic reasons).
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The technology yet requires good connections between local servers and minimum computational power for each node.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Self-driving cars encapsulate many machine learning technologies to function: computer vision for analyzing obstacles, machine learning for adapting their pace to the environment (e.g., bumpiness of the road).
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Due to the potential high number of self-driving cars and the need for them to quickly respond to real world situations, traditional cloud approach may generate safety risks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning can represent a solution for limiting volume of data transfer and accelerating learning processes.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In Industry 4.0, there is a widespread adoption of machine learning techniques to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of industrial process while guaranteeing a high level of safety.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Nevertheless, privacy of sensitive data for industries and manufacturing companies is of paramount importance.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning algorithms can be applied to these problems as they do not disclose any sensitive data.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In addition, FL also implemented for PM2.5 prediction to support Smart city sensing applications.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated learning seeks to address the problem of data governance and privacy by training algorithms collaboratively without exchanging the data itself.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Today's standard approach of centralizing data from multiple centers comes at the cost of critical concerns regarding patient privacy and data protection.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] To solve this problem, the ability to train machine learning models at scale across multiple medical institutions without moving the data is a critical technology.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Recently, a collaboration of 20 different institutions around the world validated the utility of training AI models using federated learning.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In a paper published in Nature Medicine "Federated learning for predicting clinical outcomes in patients with COVID-19", they showcased the accuracy and generalizability of a federated AI model for the prediction of oxygen needs in patients with COVID-19 infections.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Furthermore, in a published paper "A Systematic Review of Federated Learning in the Healthcare Area: From the Perspective of Data Properties and Applications", the authors trying to provide a set of challenges on FL challenges on medical data-centric perspective.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] A coalition from industry and academia has developed MedPerf, an open source platform that enables validation of medical AI models in real world data.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] The platform relies technically on federated evaluation of AI models aiming to alleviate concerns of patient privacy and conceptually on diverse benchmark committees to build the specifications of neutral clinically impactful benchmarks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Robotics includes a wide range of applications of machine learning methods: from perception and decision-making to control.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] As robotic technologies have been increasingly deployed from simple and repetitive tasks (e.g. repetitive manipulation) to complex and unpredictable tasks (e.g. autonomous navigation), the need for machine learning grows.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated Learning provides a solution to improve over conventional machine learning training methods.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In the paper, mobile robots learned navigation over diverse environments using the FL-based method, helping generalization.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In the paper, Federated Learning is applied to improve multi-robot navigation under limited communication bandwidth scenarios, which is a current challenge in real-world learning-based robotic tasks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] In the paper, Federated Learning is used to learn Vision-based navigation, helping better sim-to-real transfer.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Federated Learning (FL) is transforming biometric recognition by enabling collaborative model training across distributed data sources while preserving privacy.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] By eliminating the need to share sensitive biometric templates like fingerprints, facial images, and iris scans, FL addresses privacy concerns and regulatory constraints, allowing for improved model accuracy and generalizability.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] It mitigates challenges of data fragmentation by leveraging scattered datasets, making it particularly effective for diverse biometric applications such as facial and iris recognition.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] However, FL faces challenges, including model and data heterogeneity, computational overhead, and vulnerability to security threats like inference attacks.
[src:federated-learning/federated-learning] Future directions include developing personalized FL frameworks, enhancing system efficiency, and expanding FL applications to biometric presentation attack detection (PAD) and quality assessment, fostering innovation and robust solutions in privacy-sensitive environments.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:federated-learning/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
